    en: "A Rochester tenant fell three months behind on rent after a layoff. The landlord, frustrated with delays, changed the locks on a Tuesday morning while the tenant was at her temporary job. She returned that evening to find she could not get in. She called Legal Aid Society of Rochester. Legal Aid filed an order to show cause in Rochester Housing Court the next morning, Wednesday at 10 AM. The court issued an order requiring the landlord to restore the tenant by 5 PM that day with police backup if needed. The landlord complied. Damages followed: one night in a hotel ($95), restocking spoiled food ($120), one missed day of work ($180), and emotional distress. Total actual losses came to about $1,395. The court trebled them to $4,185. Settlement came in at $4,500 including attorney fees. After the case, the landlord properly filed a 14-day rent demand and an eviction petition; the tenant negotiated a payment plan and remained in the apartment. The whole experience cost the landlord far more than proper eviction would have."
